<DOC><DOCNO> AP890914-0171 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-89 2141EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-NuclearVenture     09-14 0270</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nuclear Venture,270</SECOND><HEAD>Reactor Makers in Joint Venture on Nuclear Services</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Nuclear reactor manufacturer Babcock andamp; WilcoxCo. said Thursday it is adding Framatome S.A. of France as a partnerin its nuclear services business and is considering a broaderpartnership to develop new commercial reactors.   Charles W. Pryor Jr., general manager of Babcock andamp; Wilcox'sexisting nuclear services business, said adding Framatome will helpBabcock andamp; Wilcox broaden its scope in an industry that bothcompanies believe is nearing a comeback in the United States.   No new nuclear plants have been ordered in the United Statessince 1978.   Framatome built and services all 55 pressurized water reactorsoperating in France.   Pryor said the venture, to be called Bandamp;W Nuclear Services Co.,based at Lynchburg, Va., will be staffed by the existing 750employees of Babcock andamp; Wilcox's services company and will be managedby Babcock andamp; Wilcox.   The deal takes effect Nov. 1.   Jean Claude Leny, chairman of Framatome, said his company ispaying $50 million for its interest in the venture, and thatoperating costs would be shared equally by the parent companies.   The $1 billion-a-year U.S. nuclear services market targeted byBabcock andamp; Wilcox includes refueling, inspection and repair of plantcomponents, maintenance, licensing and engineering support and plantmanagement services.   Pryor said Babcock andamp; Wilcox also is exploring the possibility ofan alliance with Nuclear Power International, a European groupincluding Framatome and Siemens of West Germany, to develop a newreactor design for the U.S. market.   Babcock andamp; Wilcox is a unit of McDermott International Inc., a NewOrleans-based energy concern.</TEXT></DOC>